<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Cabot Trail</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Cabot Trail</h2><p><i>Nova Scotia, Canada · Cape Breton Island, loop from Baddeck</i></p><p><b>298 km loop over three highland headlands and white-sand coves between Atlantic surf.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>248 km (154 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>7–8 hrs without stops; 2–3 days ideal</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late June–mid October (foliage early Oct is the showstopper)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Moose (genuinely common; collisions are dangerous), fog, sudden grades, narrow shoulders</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>482</td></tr></table><hr><p>Named for John Cabot's 1497 landing somewhere on this coast (the exact spot is disputed). 298 km of loop that climbs over three highland headlands and skirts white-sand coves between them. Acadian (French-speaking) on the west side; Scottish (Gaelic-speaking) on the east; Mi'kmaq throughout. Drive counterclockwise — locals prefer it because your lane is on the cliff side, with the turnouts on your right. Eat seafood chowder. Listen for ceilidh music in St Ann's. Watch the coast for whales (humpbacks, fins, minkes, occasional pilot).</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Chéticamp</b> — Acadian fishing village — French-speaking, hooked-rug heritage, Le Gabriel restaurant. Whale-watching tours from the harbor.</li><li><b>Skyline Trail</b> — 7 km loop hike to a headland boardwalk overlooking the Cabot Trail switchbacks below. Best at sunset; moose feed in the meadows.</li><li><b>Pleasant Bay</b> — Pilot whale interpretive center; tours run mid-July to August. Whale Interpretive Centre has a real pilot-whale skeleton.</li><li><b>Lone Shieling</b> — Replica of a Scottish stone shepherd's hut, set in a 350-year-old sugar maple grove. Short walk from parking.</li><li><b>Cape Smokey</b> — 365 m headland over the Atlantic — gondola-accessible, often misted in. Eagles and gannets in summer.</li><li><b>Alexander Graham Bell Museum</b> — In Baddeck — Bell summered here for 35 years. Original hydrofoil HD-4 (1919 world speed record holder) on display.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
